      <font face="Courier New, Courier, mono" size="2">



      <P>&nbsp;</P>



      <P><b>Four more haikus by Charles Henri Ford</b></P>



      <B></B> 



      <P>Weeping and wailing<br>



      And grinding of teeth ... you don’t<br>



      Have to go below</P>



      <P>I don’t know if I’ve<br>



      Settled down or not but I’m<br>



      Not moving for now</P>



      <P>You haven’t changed she<br>



      Said I thought I looked a<br>



      Little better I said</P>



      <P>If it’s worth reading<br>



        Once it’s worth reading twice so<br>



        You know where to start</P>



      <P>&nbsp;</P>



      <P><font size="1"><b>We are grateful to Penny Arcade and Indra Tamang, Ford’s 



        longtime personal assistant and frequent collaborator, for making this 



        interview possible. For more information on <I>View</I>, we recommend 



        Charles Henri Ford (ed.),<I> View: Parade of the Avant-Garde, 1940-1947</I> 



        (with a preface by Paul Bowles), New York: Thunder Mouth, 1991 </b></font></P>



      <P><b><font size="1">The interview was conducted at Charles Henri Ford’s 



        New York apartment on May 2, 2000. It is preserved in part as a digital 



        videotape (filmed by Martin Samsel) and available in full on audiocassette. 



        &copy; ASRL, 2000.</font></b></P>



      </font> 



